1. What is Java?
Java is a high-level, object-oriented programming language.
It follows WORA (Write Once, Run Anywhere) using JVM.
Code → compiled to bytecode → runs on JVM.

2. Java Program Structure
class Hello {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello World");
    }
}

3. Key Points:
class → blueprint of program
main() → entry point
System.out.println() → prints output

3. Data Types:
i) Primitive Types:
Type	Size	Example
int	4 bytes	10
float	4 bytes	10.5f
double	8 bytes	10.99
char	2 bytes	'A'
boolean	1 bit true/false

ii) Non-Primitive:
String
Arrays
Classes

4. Variables
int a = 10;
float b = 5.5f;
String name = "John";

5. Operators
Arithmetic:

+ - * / %

Relational:

== != > < >= <=

Logical:

&& || !

6. Control Statements
if-else:
if(a > 10){
    System.out.println("Greater");
} else {
    System.out.println("Smaller");
}
switch:
switch(day){
    case 1: System.out.println("Monday"); break;
    default: System.out.println("Invalid");
}

7. Loops
for loop:
for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++){
    System.out.println(i);
}
while loop:
int i = 0;
while(i < 5){
    i++;
}
do-while:
do{
    i++;
}while(i < 5);

 8. Arrays
int arr[] = {1, 2, 3, 4};
System.out.println(arr[0]);

9. Strings
String s = "Java";
System.out.println(s.length());
System.out.println(s.toUpperCase());





